278
00:15:36,852 --> 00:15:38,270
I'm afraid that...

279
00:15:38,979 --> 00:15:42,024
I won't be able to work any longer.

280
00:15:45,653 --> 00:15:46,487
All right.

281
00:16:24,900 --> 00:16:30,948
STRATEGY ANALYSIS TEAM LEADER,
YOO KYUNG-TAEK

282
00:16:41,041 --> 00:16:44,586
The interview of Gil Chang-ju
by Kim Young-chae will be

283
00:16:44,670 --> 00:16:47,381
broadcast the week after next week.

284
00:16:47,464 --> 00:16:50,551
Chang-ju can pitch balls well for sure.

285
00:16:50,801 --> 00:16:54,722
Young-chae said his pitches were
the best among what she saw

286
00:16:54,805 --> 00:16:56,807
around the clubs this winter.

287
00:16:57,558 --> 00:17:00,394
Were you there
for the interview she was doing?

288
00:17:00,477 --> 00:17:01,729
Yes, of course.

289
00:17:01,812 --> 00:17:05,024
-Any problematic questions?
-I told her repeatedly.

290
00:17:05,107 --> 00:17:07,317
It was mainly focused on today's pitching,

291
00:17:07,401 --> 00:17:09,903
and his resolution for the future.

292
00:17:09,987 --> 00:17:13,657
I know she adds some
personal opinions in the studio

293
00:17:13,741 --> 00:17:14,658
outside the interview.

294
00:17:14,742 --> 00:17:16,201
Are you also her fan?

295
00:17:16,285 --> 00:17:18,412
That's the secret to her popularity.

296
00:17:18,495 --> 00:17:20,664
She engages viewers with her journalism.

297
00:17:20,748 --> 00:17:22,374
And also,

298
00:17:23,042 --> 00:17:24,126
she's pretty.

299
00:17:25,753 --> 00:17:28,505
The opinions that she adds in the studio

300
00:17:28,589 --> 00:17:30,591
could get us in trouble.

301
00:17:30,674 --> 00:17:32,676
No way.

302
00:17:32,760 --> 00:17:34,762
She won't be giving up her chance
to cover our club.

303
00:17:34,845 --> 00:17:35,971
Have you told her not to?

304
00:17:36,597 --> 00:17:37,765
No.

305
00:17:37,931 --> 00:17:41,560
She'll keep hitting our sore spots
and think it's journalism.

306
00:17:45,773 --> 00:17:47,316
Should I call her?

307
00:17:47,399 --> 00:17:48,400
No.

308
00:17:48,484 --> 00:17:49,485
I'll...

309
00:17:50,611 --> 00:17:52,154
make sure.

310
00:17:52,654 --> 00:17:55,157
The salary negotiation
of our players is coming soon.

311
00:17:55,240 --> 00:17:58,494
As soon as I get the raw data
regarding the negotiation,

312
00:17:58,577 --> 00:17:59,411
I'll hand it over.

313
00:17:59,495 --> 00:18:00,329
RAW DATA

314
00:18:00,412 --> 00:18:01,246
Yes.

315
00:18:01,330 --> 00:18:02,873
We'll prepare to get the data.

316
00:18:02,956 --> 00:18:04,374
It'll be arduous.

317
00:18:05,876 --> 00:18:07,753
Because upper management
thinks players are

318
00:18:07,836 --> 00:18:09,963
obsessed with money
when they're not even good,

319
00:18:10,547 --> 00:18:13,675
the total amount of salaries is low
considering our bad record.

320
00:18:14,843 --> 00:18:17,971
But it's something we get done
somehow every year.

321
00:18:18,055 --> 00:18:19,431
And...

322
00:18:20,015 --> 00:18:22,476
Lee Jin-bum of the strategy analysis team

323
00:18:22,559 --> 00:18:24,686
-decided to quit.
-Jin-bum?

324
00:18:24,770 --> 00:18:27,397
But he was a reliable employee.

325
00:18:27,481 --> 00:18:29,900
His family runs a big orchard,
and he went there.

326
00:18:29,983 --> 00:18:31,151
An orchard?

327
00:18:32,694 --> 00:18:35,489
That is some reason to quit.

328
00:18:36,365 --> 00:18:38,826
The employees of your division
are being replaced quite often.

329
00:18:38,909 --> 00:18:41,620
Kids these days can't stand long
if you treat them too harshly.

330
00:18:41,703 --> 00:18:43,831
We need someone who can work longer.

331
00:18:44,790 --> 00:18:46,625
For the scout and strategy analysis teams,

332
00:18:46,708 --> 00:18:48,752
it's never good to change staff often.

333
00:18:49,044 --> 00:18:51,296
-Isn't it?
-How about

334
00:18:51,672 --> 00:18:54,049
we hire one
through open recruitment this time?

335
00:18:56,426 --> 00:18:57,261
Why?

336
00:18:57,344 --> 00:19:00,389
Jin-bum used to handle data,

337
00:19:00,472 --> 00:19:02,224
so rather than a former player...

338
00:19:02,307 --> 00:19:03,851
It's someone that I can work with.

339
00:19:03,934 --> 00:19:07,020
I know that.
That's why I'm just suggesting.

340
00:19:08,438 --> 00:19:10,232
Since we're at it,

341
00:19:10,315 --> 00:19:14,361
I think our teams are too closed
when it comes to sabermetrics.

342
00:19:14,444 --> 00:19:16,822
If the experts in that area
apply for the job,

343
00:19:17,573 --> 00:19:19,867
it wouldn't hurt to talk to them once.

344
00:19:19,950 --> 00:19:22,327
How would I work
with someone I don't know?

345
00:19:23,412 --> 00:19:26,290
I've never interfered in the recruitment
of the operations team,

346
00:19:26,373 --> 00:19:27,916
and I don't plan to in the future.

347
00:19:28,584 --> 00:19:30,335
I prefer not to work with someone

348
00:19:30,419 --> 00:19:32,629
who hasn't struck out anyone
or hit a home run before.

349
00:19:35,507 --> 00:19:39,136
Whether it's black or white,
a cat merely has to hunt mice well.

350
00:19:42,848 --> 00:19:45,934
I also haven't struck out anyone
or hit a home run before.

351
00:19:49,938 --> 00:19:51,315
In the Major League,

352
00:19:51,398 --> 00:19:54,401
the number of coaches
who weren't athletes is growing.

353
00:19:54,484 --> 00:19:57,863
Also, an analyst works close
to the players.

354
00:19:57,946 --> 00:19:59,281
In the Pelicans,

355
00:19:59,364 --> 00:20:03,285
I know that a sabermetrics expert
is working as an analyst.

356
00:20:03,368 --> 00:20:04,828
And they're not doing so bad.

357
00:20:04,912 --> 00:20:06,079
I believe

358
00:20:06,163 --> 00:20:09,416
someone with experience
in playing baseball sees things better.

359
00:20:09,499 --> 00:20:12,961
I still practice batting every morning.
Do you know why?

360
00:20:13,629 --> 00:20:14,963
I wouldn't know.

361
00:20:16,131 --> 00:20:18,884
The players won't even listen to me
if I'm not in shape.

362
00:20:19,676 --> 00:20:21,929
No matter how hard I try
to analyze the data

363
00:20:22,012 --> 00:20:24,139
and tell them to fix this and that
with the videos,

364
00:20:24,223 --> 00:20:26,558
they still say they know
their own bodies best.

365
00:20:27,267 --> 00:20:29,436
And you think an ordinary person
could tell them

366
00:20:29,519 --> 00:20:31,730
what to do because they've
watched a few baseball videos?

367
00:20:32,105 --> 00:20:33,148
Do you think they'd listen?

368
00:20:36,235 --> 00:20:39,321
If it were me, I'd rather fix
their misconception

369
00:20:39,404 --> 00:20:42,658
instead of changing myself
to their standard.

370
00:20:47,412 --> 00:20:49,831
Let's do an open recruitment.

371
00:20:49,915 --> 00:20:51,917
Have the one you recommended apply, too.

372
00:20:52,709 --> 00:20:55,337
Let's end our meeting here.

373
00:20:57,047 --> 00:20:58,006
-Good work.
-Thanks.

374
00:20:59,800 --> 00:21:03,220
He says catching a mouse
is all that matters.

375
00:21:09,893 --> 00:21:11,728
I can catch your pitches
with my eyes closed.

376
00:21:11,812 --> 00:21:13,313
What? Hey.

377
00:21:13,397 --> 00:21:15,232
Don't you know
I'm just playing catch with you?

378
00:21:15,315 --> 00:21:18,193
